  "prompt": "How soon after implantation bleeding would a test be negative?",
  "response": "Implantation bleeding typically occurs about 6-12 days after conception, when the fertilized egg attaches to the uterine lining. Pregnancy tests detect the hormone **human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG)**, which begins to be produced after implantation.\n\nHere\u2019s a general timeline:\n\n1. **Implantation occurs**: 6-12 days after conception.  \n2. **hCG production starts**: Immediately after implantation, but levels are very low at first.  \n3. **hCG becomes detectable**: It usually takes 1-2 days after implantation for hCG levels to rise enough to be detected by a **sensitive pregnancy test**.  \n\nIf you take a pregnancy test **too soon after implantation bleeding**, it could be negative because hCG levels may not yet be high enough to detect. For the most accurate results:  \n\n- **Wait at least 1-2 days after implantation bleeding** to test.  \n- **Use a sensitive early-detection test** (these can detect lower levels of hCG).  \n- If the test is negative but you still suspect pregnancy, wait a few more days and retest, as hCG levels double every 48-72 hours in early pregnancy.  \n\nIf you\u2019re unsure about the timing or results, consulting a healthcare provider is always the best course of action.",
